      <!-- SECTION 3 — WHY CONVERT KRUTIDEV TO UNICODE? -->
      <section class="border-t border-slate-200/60 dark:border-slate-800/60 pt-10">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100 tracking-tight mb-4">
          Why convert KrutiDev to Unicode?
        </h2>
        <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          KrutiDev 010 — also known as Kruti Dev — was the dominant Hindi font 
          across Indian government offices, DTP shops, and print publishing 
          through the 1990s and 2000s. It works by mapping Devanagari glyphs 
          directly onto English keyboard keys, which made it practical for 
          typewriter-era workflows but created a fundamental problem: the text 
          is unreadable without the font installed.
        </p>

        <!-- Two-column comparison box -->
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
          <!-- Left Column -->
