      <!-- SECTION 6 — UNDERSTANDING HINDI LEGACY FONTS -->
      <section class="border-t border-slate-200/60 dark:border-slate-800/60 pt-10">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100 tracking-tight mb-6">
          Understanding Hindi legacy fonts
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-5">
          <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">What is KrutiDev?</strong> KrutiDev (KrutiDev 010) is a non-Unicode Hindi font that dominated Indian typing from the 1990s onward. It encodes Devanagari characters by remapping them onto standard English keyboard positions — so the letter "d" in KrutiDev displays as "ि" (short i matra), not the English letter D. This made it practical for early Hindi DTP but invisible to any modern system that doesn't have the font.
          </p>

          <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">What is Mangal font?</strong> Mangal is a Unicode-compliant Devanagari font developed by Microsoft and bundled with Windows. Unlike KrutiDev, Mangal uses proper Unicode code points — making text stored in Mangal readable by search engines, screen readers, and any modern system. It is the mandated font for most Indian government digital workflows and e-governance portals.
          </p>

          <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">What is Chanakya font?</strong> Chanakya is another legacy non-Unicode Hindi font widely used in Indian newspaper and magazine publishing — particularly in PageMaker-based print workflows. Like KrutiDev, it uses its own proprietary character mapping incompatible with KrutiDev, which is why pasting KrutiDev text and applying Chanakya font produces garbled output rather than correct Hindi.
          </p>

          <p class="text-xs sm:text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <strong class="font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">KrutiDev vs Unicode — which should you use?</strong> For any new document, website, or system, use Unicode. For working with existing legacy archives, government systems that haven't upgraded, or DTP shops still running Chanakya or KrutiDev — that's exactly what this converter is for.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

